This is meaningless in the UK as local legislation takes precedence over foreign (yes even Californian!!) law.<br>
<br>
Local contract law (what constitutes a legal and 'fair' contract), human rights legislation (and yes this is relevant as invasion of privacy is a violation of human rights under UK law - this has caused our government many headaches on their own 'eavesdropping' legislation), 'National Security' Legislation, and of course local privacy laws (such as they are - very limited in the UK) all over-ride foreign statute.<br>
<br>
<br>
The arguments that only criminals have anything to fear has been suitably rebuffed by other posters - but I for one am horrified that intelligent people really believe this - and of course it is the first argument of the fascist state:  'you've got nothing to fear if you've nothing to hide' - in a word bullsh*t!<br>
<br>
I have nothing to hide -  but I am damned if I am going to be happy about some private US company having access to my files and what processes I happen to be running on my PC.<br>
